<subSubSection id="CFF1651AFFFD8131D794FBD75525B5BE" pageId="6" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="87543691FFFD8131D794FBD75187B690" blockId="6.[151,1437,582,1219]" pageId="6">
<emphasis id="B59FEA83FFFD8131D794FBD7513CB660" bold="true" box="[199,315,1050,1075]" pageId="6">Remarks.</emphasis>
This species closely resembles 
<taxonomicName id="40EB4D12FFFD8131D5CDFBD6530AB660" box="[670,781,1050,1075]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Aconurella" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="6" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="furcata">
<emphasis id="B59FEA83FFFD8131D5CDFBD6530AB660" box="[670,781,1050,1075]" italics="true" pageId="6">A. furcata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in having the male pygofer with darkly sclerotized part on the posteroventral margin more than its half its length and connective arms wide apart from each other, but it differs from the latter by the following features: pygofer dorsoapical margin with 2–3 dark spinules; style apophysis less than 2 times longer than preapical lobe; row of short spinules present near base of anal tube; subgenital plate shorter than pygofer.
</paragraph>
